Part 3

Rohan took the body back to Odisha. The head office had sent a private ambulance, the white Ambassador kind, the driver wearing the company uniform with the grey epaulettes on the shoulders. 

Rohan did not speak to Adarsh. He stood near the casualty counter, signed the release forms, his signature neat, clear, and steady—the signature he had learned to write after Vikram left the board.

His hand did not tremble today. The red Nandyal dust had gone from his shoes, replaced by polished black leather that reflected the bright hospital corridor lights.

Ananya and Sarita left in the evening. They had the Howrah train tickets, ready to return to Bagbazar.

"Come to Bagbazar, Dr. Tripathy," Sarita said, pausing at the hospital gate. "The neem trees are green now."

"I will come," Adarsh said.

He watched the auto rickshaw carry them away toward the station, its yellow and green frame disappearing into the traffic. Ananya was sitting in the back, the three-legged wooden horse kept on her lap, her hand holding the green ledger tight. 

She did not look back.

---

Adarsh returned to his small hospital quarters room at eight. The room was small, smelling of old paper, damp brick, and the cup of tea he had left unfinished on the side table.

He went to the wooden cupboard near the corner. He opened the lowest shelf, reaching behind the old medical journals and the dusty folders of forgotten cases.

The pathology textbook was still there. He pulled it out.

The cover was grey with the dust of twenty-two years, the corners frayed, the cardboard backing showing through the peeling blue paper.

He opened the book. He turned to Chapter three: *Hepatic cirrhosis.*

The line was still there, the blue ink of Vicky's pen dry and faded, ending mid-sentence near the paper margin. 

*Decompensated liver function is marked by portal hypertension...*

He closed the book slowly. He kept it on the desk near his stethoscope.

Vikram had left the room. He had left the white coat, the fourteen hundred crore, and the seventy-six hundred crore. 

Most people who wrote his obituary in the business weekly would write about the empire he had surrendered. They would call him a loser. 

They would say he was a tycoon who couldn't keep his grip on the wheel, a success that had gone soft at the end.

Adarsh walked to the window. The hospital lights below were yellow, shining on the wet asphalt of the M.G. Road. 

The auto rickshaws honked. The vendors shouted. The city went on.

But as he looked at his own white apron hanging on the wooden peg on the wall, the blue thread stitching on the pocket—*Adarsh Tripathy*—still neat and clear after thirty years of shifts, he wondered.

Who is the loser? 

Is it he? Or is it we, who sit in our comfortable chairs, making comfortable decisions, holding onto our names until the name is the only thing left of us?

He had no answer. The book on the table was closed, and the window was dark. 

And the story of Vikram Ahuja had ended exactly where it began—on a wooden bench, under the shadow of a neem tree, with a glass of red tea that had gone cold in the wind.

[End of Novel]
